text.tspan: A 20-minute dice game for up to eight players
EQUIPMENT:
You will need 5 6-sided dice, and pencil and paper
for keeping score.
HOW TO PLAY:
Players take turns throwing 1-5 of the dice, up to three
times, trying to get one of the hands. There are 6 number
hands (1-6), and four special hands.
For the number hands, the goal is to roll as many of one
of the numbers as possible; only those add to your score.
Examples:
For the “twos” hand, rolling 2,3,4,2,2 gives a score
of 6-- add up the 2's.
2,4,5,2,5 could give a score of 10 for the 5's slot,
but it could also be a 2's score of 4. Going with 2's would
save the 5's slot for a luckier turn.
There are four special hands:
Escalera: 1,2,3,4,5 or 2,3,4,5,6: 20 points.
Un Full: a “full house”, two of a kind and three of a
different kind: 30 points.
Poker: four of a kind: 40 points
Grande: five of a kind: 50 points.
The special hands don't give partial scores; a player
who never rolls a de mano, gets no points for that slot.
After the last roll, the player chooses which hand
fits the roll best, and writes the score in that slot.
If a player decides to throw only once, their roll is
called “de mano,” and they get an extra 5 points.
A “Grande de Mano” instantly wins the game.
WINNING:
Add up the scores after every player has had nine turns.
High score wins.
